Happy Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month! This year's theme is Advancing Leader through Collaboration. This is a timely call to action particularly in terms of healthcare. Over the last few years, leaders have had to collaborate more than ever with other members of the healthcare team, with patients, with technology, and with a scared public in order to save lives. As we celebrate the contributions of Asiam Americans and Pacific Islanders, we want to highlight the ways in which their work has contributed to the healthcare landscape. Thank you for all you do to advance healthcare for all Americans.

Happy Jewish American Heritage Month! Established by the presidential proclamation in 2006, and renewed every year since, JAHM provides an opportunity for all Americans to celebrate and draw inspiration from the contributions that Jewish Americans have made to our nation's history and culture. During this month, we want to take time to honor those Jewish American who have left a significant imprint on the healthcare field. Despite enduring discrimination and other obstacles, these individuals created a path for other Jewish American healthcare providers to follow and even more importantly provide culturally sensitive patient care to patients of their same heritage and beyond. Thank you for all that you do and the contributions youï¿½ve made to healthcare in the United States! #OurSharedHeritage #JewishAmericanHeritageMonth

In May, we share in a celebration of the diverse cultures and rich stories of the Asian American and Pacific Islander communities. We recognize their influence and impact throughout history, and we wish everyone a happy #AAPIHeritageMonth.

Abdullah ibn Umar (RA) said: "We lived during an instant of time in which one of us would receive Imaan first before receiving the Qur'an. And when the Surahs were revealed to (Prophet) Muhammad (pbuh), we would learn what they permitted and what they prohibited and what they commanded and what they forbade and what should be the stance towards them. But I have seen many men, from whom one is given the Qur'an before Imaan, and he reads it from the opening of the Book to its closing and he does not know what it orders and what it forbids and what should be his stance towards it. He is like someone who is just throwing out dates." Subhanaâ€™Allah! This is such a powerful narration and perfectly encapsulates what the Prophet (pbuh) set out to do during the initial stages of Islam. We need to pause and rethink what approach we are undertaking when raising our children? How are we teaching our children and what are we focussing first few years of teaching the deen to them? I have so much to share. Peanut Butter White Russian Ingredients 1.5 ounces Blind Squirrel Peanut Butter Whiskey .75 ounce Cafe Bueno Coffee Liqueur .5 ounce half and half or heavy cream Instructions Fill a rocks glass with ice. Pour in the peanut butter whiskey, then the coffee liqueur. Slowly pour the half and half over the top. Stir slowly to combine the ingredients. Alternatively, some people prefer their White Russian shaken. This creates a super frothy drink. Shop for ingredients at Kappys.com or on the Kappyâ€™s App.

We continue with Black History Month in Talbot County with the story of Unionville - an African-American community settled in 1867 by ex-slaves and free Blacks who had fought in the Union Army (1863-1867) during Americaâ€™s Civil War. A short drive from Easton, the settlementâ€™s formation is credited to the Ezekiel Cowgill family, Quakers and ardent abolitionists who offered each of the eighteen veterans a plot of land at the rate of one dollar a year for thirty years. Named in honor of the Union Army that the veterans credited with winning their freedom, you can read more about Unionville then add it to your Visit Talbot County To-Do List! https://talbothistory.org/collections-research/black-history/unionville/ - #talbotcountymd #blackhistorymonth Maryland #mdinfocus Discover Easton Town of St. Michaels, Maryland Town of Oxford, MD Trappe, Maryland Unionville, Maryland Talbot Historical Society

In 2000s, during the administration of President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo, she supported the Framework Plan for Women which aimed to promote womenâ€™s economic empowerment, protect womenâ€™s human rights, and promote and strengthen gender-responsive governance. It served as the governmentâ€™s guide in planning and budgeting for GAD programs and projects, and activities. In 2004, Republic Act no. 9262, also known as the Anti-Violence Against Women and their Children (VAWC), was enacted. This Act penalizes the commission of violence against women and their children (VAWC) in the context of domestic violence or violence in intimate relationships. In 2006, the Gender-Responsive Economic Actions for the Transformation of Women (GREAT Women) Project was implemented. It is a governance and capacity development project that aimed to promote and support a gender-responsive enabling environment for womenâ€™s economic empowerment, specifically those in the micro enterprise. In 2008, the Philippine government has received commendation from the Association of South East Asian Nationsâ€™ member-states for the countryâ€™s success in closing the gender gap by promoting human development opportunities. The Philippines has successfully maintained its 6th rank in the Global Gender Index. On 14 August 2009, Republic Act No. 9710 or the Magna Carta of Women was signed. It is a comprehensive womenâ€™s rights law that seeks to eliminate discrimination against women by recognizing, protecting, fulfilling and promoting the rights of Filipino women, especially those in the marginalized sectors. It also expanded the functions of then NCRFW subsequently changing its name to the Philippine Commission on Women. #WomenMakeChange #NWMC2022 #AgendaNgKababaihan Photos c/o https://pcw.gov.ph/gloria-macapagal-arroyo/

Lucretia Mott was a founder of the Philadelphia Female Anti-Slavery Society, an organization that championed for racial and gender equity established in 1833. Mott is remembered as an abolitionist, women's rights activist and social reformer. #WomensHistoryMonth

ROCK, PAPER, PAINT: ART OF THE PEOPLE Online preview: Tuesday, March 8, from 7pm to 9pm Screening and filmmaker Q&A with special guests Inspired by the controversy that erupted when local artists painted "Black Lives Matter" on the Bernal Rock, filmmaker Audrey Daniel set out to explore the question, "Should art transcend politics, or politics transcend art?" This work-in-progress (the first part of a two-part documentary), features interviews with Bay Area artists, including Precita Eyes Muralists' Susan Cervantes, and others instrumental in creating public art intended to provoke discussion and introspection around issues of social justice, inequality and racism. Following the film, you're invited to a panel discussion with the filmmaker and local activists Patricia Rose (artist and mural tour coordinator for Precita Eyes), and Buck Bagot, Bernal Heights community organizer. Register here: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/rock-paper-paint-art-of-the-people-face-to-face-with-the-filmmaker-tickets-264798849487:=:https://www.eventbrite.com/e/264798849487

ğŸ‘ A federal jury last week awarded $1.5 million to a Black transgender woman who had filed suit against two Atlanta police officers for jailing her on a false drug trafficking charge, in a case that shed light on an incentive system run by the cityâ€™s police that a judge said could lead to discrimination. In October 2015, Juâ€™Zema Goldring was crossing the street in midtown Atlanta with friends, after having recently moved to Georgia from Maryland. She was stopped for jaywalking by Atlanta police officers Vladimir Henry and Juan Restrepo, who then took her into custody on grounds that she could be trafficking cocaine. The officers focused on the fact that Goldring had been carrying a stress ball, saying it could be hiding drugs. She told the officers to cut open the ball and test its contents, one of her attorneys, Miguel Dominguez, said in a phone interview. Henry complied, conducting multiple tests. All of them turned out negative. At one point, as â€œa visibly frustratedâ€ Henry was testing the stress ballâ€™s contents, Goldring heard another Atlanta police officer who was passing by Henryâ€™s desk telling him to â€œgive it up buddy, itâ€™s not a drug,â€ according to Dominguez. But he didnâ€™t. Henry filed an arrest warrant against Goldring, saying she had been carrying illegal substances. Goldring ended up in jail and wouldnâ€™t be released until almost six months later, in March 2016, after prosecutors realized the drug tests in fact had been negative. The Georgia Bureau of Investigation completed its own tests on the sand inside Goldringâ€™s stress ball, more than a month after her arrest, and they were negative, as well. Judge William M. Ray II, who oversaw the lawsuitâ€¦ (more @washingtonpost)

Today during Asian American, Native Hawaiian, and Pacific Islander American Heritage Month, we give a spotlight to Ushma Upadhyay from UCSF. In a recent article, Upadhyay and coauthors found that the median patient out-of-pocket charges increased for medication abortion and first trimester procedural abortion during 2017-20 by thirteen and twenty-one percent, respectively. Read the full article here: https://bit.ly/3M0Skt0:=:https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/10.1377/hlthaff.2021.01528?utm_medium=social&utm_source=facebook&utm_campaign=elevating+voices&utm_content=aapi+heritage+month&utm_term=upadhyay

Today during Asian American, Native Hawaiian, and Pacific Islander Heritage Month and as part of our Elevating Voices series, we give a spotlight to Stella Yi from NYU Grossman School of Medicine. In a recent Health Affairs paper featured in the Racism & Health issue, Dr. Yi and coauthors describe poor-quality data infrastructure and biases in the health care sector fueled by stereotypes about Asian Americans, and they elucidate how these examples of structural racism act independently and reinforce one another to harm health outcomes. Read the full article here: https://bit.ly/380yRu1:=:https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/full/10.1377/hlthaff.2021.01417?utm_medium=social&utm_source=facebook&utm_campaign=elevating+voices&utm_content=aapi+heritage+month&utm_term=yi

ICYMI: Racism & Health in US Medicine: A Conversation With Harriet Washington. https://bit.ly/3J8WayA:=:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVPFUlRAgUU Dr. Aletha Maybank, American Medical Association (AMA)'s Chief Health Equity Officer and Dr. Vabren Watts, Health Affairs' Director of Health Equity, interviews Harriet Washington, author of Medical Apartheid: The Dark History of Medical Experimentation on Black Americans from Colonial Times to the Present (2006), as she addresses the history of racism in medicine and research in the US.

ICYMI: Racism & Health in US Medicine: A Conversation With Harriet Washington. https://bit.ly/3J8WayA:=:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVPFUlRAgUU Dr. Aletha Maybank, American Medical Association (AMA)'s Chief Health Equity Officer and Dr. Vabren Watts, Health Affairs' Director of Health Equity, interviews Harriet Washington, author of Medical Apartheid: The Dark History of Medical Experimentation on Black Americans from Colonial Times to the Present (2006), as she addresses the history of racism in medicine and research in the US.

In their new paper featured in the Racism & Health issue, Patricia Homan from Florida State University and Tyson Brown from Duke University linked administrative data on disproportionate felony disenfranchisement of Black residents across US states to individual-level health data from the 2016 Health and Retirement Study. After adjusting for individual- and state-level factors, they found that â€œresiding in states with higher levels of racialized [electoral] disenfranchisement was associated with more depressive symptoms, more functional limitations,â€ and more difficulty performing daily living tasks among Black people than among White middle-aged and older adults. Read the full article here: https://bit.ly/3v0Mpys:=:https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/10.1377/hlthaff.2021.01414

In their paper featured in this monthâ€™s issue dedicated to racism and health, Stella Yi from NYU Langone Health and coauthors describe poor-quality data infrastructure and biases in the health care sector fueled by stereotypes about Asian Americans, and they elucidate how these examples of structural racism act independently and reinforce one other to harm health outcomes. Read the full article here: https://bit.ly/3opY85T:=:https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/10.1377/hlthaff.2021.01417

In their new Health Affairs paper featured in this monthâ€™s issue on racism and health, Ruqaiijah Yearby from Saint Louis University and coauthors explore the racist roots of past and present health policy as it relates to coverage, financing, and quality. Read the full article here: https://bit.ly/3omgl44:=:https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/full/10.1377/hlthaff.2021.01466?utm_medium=social&utm_source=facebook&utm_campaign=february2022issue&utm_content=yearby

In a new overview paper featured in this monthâ€™s issue dedicated to racism and health, Ruth Enid Zambrana from the University of Maryland and David Williams from Harvard University describe the rich empirical foundation for the conclusion that racism is a determinant of health that must be addressed to achieve health equity. â€œThe early twenty-first century has benefited from multiple strands of intersectional scholarship that clearly delineated social determinants, wealth and assets, and structural racism as critical factors in health disparities,â€ they wrote. Read the full article here: https://bit.ly/34Fpkqg:=:https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/10.1377/hlthaff.2021.01439

Since the latest parliamentary elections in March 2021, the world has looked upon Israelâ€™s government wondering if the coalition would last. It is still standing almost a year later and looks like it will remain intact until at least September 2023, when Yair Lapid is scheduled to take over as Prime Minister. Nonetheless, key issues remain that threaten the stability of the coalition. For example, recent settler violence in the West Bank, debates over the citizenship law, and balancing Israeli foreign vs. domestic policy have all been contentious topics that have sparked inter and intra-party friction in the coalition. Furthermore, questions revolving around Netenyahuâ€™s future in the government threaten the sustainability of the alliance, as he is the paradoxical glue holding it together. With just a one-seat majority in parliament, this coalition government cannot afford to lose one of its parties, or it will fall. Thus, these issues must be handled with extreme caution, or Israelis may head to their 5th election in two years. Join us to discuss with David Makovsky-- the Ziegler distinguished fellow and director of the Washington Institute for Near East Policy Project on the Middle East Peace Process. Dr. Makovsky has extensive experience covering events in Israel as a journalist, researcher, and advisor on peace negotiations between the Israelis and Palestinian and will provide crucial insight into the state of the Israeli coalition today.
